# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: connecting-rod
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:connecting-rod/2024-aluminium-alloy] 2024 is commonly extruded, and also available in alclad sheet and plate forms.
[src:connecting-rod/2024-aluminium-alloy] It is not commonly forged; the related 2014 aluminium alloy is, though.
[src:connecting-rod/2024-aluminium-alloy] Aluminium alloy 2024 has a density of 2.78 g/cm3 (0.1 lb/in3), electrical conductivity of 30% IACS, Young's modulus of 73 GPa (10.6 Msi) across all tempers, and begins to melt at 500 °C (932 °F).
[src:connecting-rod/2024-aluminium-alloy] The mechanical properties of 2024 depend greatly on the temper of the material.
[src:connecting-rod/2024-aluminium-alloy] 2024-O temper aluminium has no heat treating.
[src:connecting-rod/2024-aluminium-alloy] It has an ultimate tensile strength of 140–210 MPa (21–30 ksi), and a maximum yield strength of no more than 97 MPa (14,000 psi).
[src:connecting-rod/2024-aluminium-alloy] The material has elongation (stretch before ultimate failure) of 10–25%, this is the allowable range per applicable AMS specifications.
[src:connecting-rod/2024-aluminium-alloy] T3 temper 2024 sheet has an ultimate tensile strength of 400–430 MPa (58–62 ksi) and yield strength of at least 270–280 MPa (39–40 ksi).
[src:connecting-rod/2024-aluminium-alloy] Solution treated at foundry and naturally aged.
[src:connecting-rod/2024-aluminium-alloy] Cooled from hot-working and artificially aged (at elevated temperature).
[src:connecting-rod/2024-aluminium-alloy] T351 temper 2024 plate has an ultimate tensile strength of 470 MPa (68 ksi) and yield strength of 280 MPa (41 ksi).
[src:connecting-rod/2024-aluminium-alloy] Due to its high strength and fatigue resistance, 2024 is widely used in aircraft, especially wing and fuselage structures under tension.
[src:connecting-rod/2024-aluminium-alloy] Additionally, since the material is susceptible to thermal shock, 2024 is used in the qualification of liquid penetrant tests outside of normal temperature ranges.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] 7075 aluminium alloy's composition roughly includes 5.6–6.1% zinc, 2.1–2.5% magnesium, 1.2–1.6% copper, and less than a half percent of silicon, iron, manganese, titanium, chromium, and other metals.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] The first 7075 was developed by a Japanese company, Sumitomo Metal, in 1935, and eventually used for airframe production in the Imperial Japanese Navy.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] 7075 was reverse engineered by Alcoa in 1943, after examining a captured Japanese aircraft.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] 7075 was standardized for aerospace use in 1945.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] Aluminium 7075A has a density of 2.810 g/cm3.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] The mechanical properties of 7075 depend greatly on the tempering of the material.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] Aluminium 7075 has a low formability at low room temperature and is vulnerable to stress corrosion cracking.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] Using different elevated temperature forming techniques has been shown to reduce springback and fracture.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] Examples of those elevated temperature forming techniques are retrogression forming and warm forming.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] Un-heat-treated 7075 (7075-0 temper) has a maximum tensile strength of no more than 280 MPa (40,000 psi), and maximum yield strength of no more than 140 MPa (21,000 psi).
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] The material has an elongation (stretch before ultimate failure) of 9–10%.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] As is the case for all 7075 aluminium alloys, 7075-0 is highly corrosion-resistant combined with generally acceptable strength profile.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] The T6 temper is usually achieved by homogenizing the cast 7075 at 450 °C for several hours, quenching, and then ageing at 120 °C for 24 hours.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] This yields the peak strength of the 7075 alloys.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] The strength is derived mainly from finely dispersed eta and eta' precipitates both within grains and along grain boundaries.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] T651 temper 7075 has an ultimate tensile strength of 570 MPa (83,000 psi) and yield strength of 500 MPa (73,000 psi).
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] These properties can change depending on the form of material used.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] The thicker plates may exhibit lower strengths and elongation than the numbers listed above.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] T7 temper has an ultimate tensile strength of 505 MPa (73,200 psi) and a yield strength of 435 MPa (63,100 psi).
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] T7 temper is achieved by overaging (meaning aging past the peak hardness) the material.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] This is often accomplished by aging at 100–120 °C for several hours and then at 160–180 °C for 24 hours or more.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] The T7 temper produces a microstructure of mostly eta precipitates.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] In contrast to the T6 temper, these eta particles are much larger and prefer growth along the grain boundaries.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] This reduces the susceptibility to stress corrosion cracking.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] The retrogression and reage (RRA) temper is a multistage heat treatment temper.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] Starting with a sheet in the T6 temper, it involves overaging past peak hardness (T6 temper) to near the T7 temper.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] A subsequent reaging at 120 °C for 24 hours returns the hardness and strength to or very nearly to T6 temper levels.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] RRA treatments can be accomplished with many different procedures.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] The general guidelines are retrogressing between 180 and 240 °C for 15 min 10 s.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] The world's first mass-production usage of the 7075 aluminium alloy was for the Mitsubishi A6M Zero fighter.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] The aircraft was known for its excellent maneuverability which was facilitated by the higher strength of 7075 compared to previous aluminium alloys.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] 7000 series alloys such as 7075 are often used in transport applications due to their high specific strength, including marine, automotive and aviation.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] These same properties lead to its use in rock climbing equipment, bicycle components, inline-skating-frames and hang glider airframes are commonly made from 7075 aluminium alloy.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] Hobby-grade RC models commonly use 7075 and 6061 for chassis plates.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] 7075 is used in the manufacturing of M16 rifles for the U.S. military as well as AR-15 style rifles for the civilian market.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] In particular high-quality M16 rifle lower and upper receivers, as well as extension tubes, are typically made from 7075-T6 alloy.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] Desert Tactical Arms, SIG Sauer, and French armament company PGM use it for their precision rifles.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] It is also commonly used in shafts for lacrosse sticks, such as the STX sabre, and camping knife and fork sets.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] It is a common material used in competition yo-yos as well.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] Another application for the 7075-series alloy has been in connecting rods used in drag racing engines.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] Aluminium connecting rods do not have the fatigue life of forged steel rods, but have less mass than their steel counterparts, resulting in lower mechanical stress during periods in which an engine is operated under full-throttle, high-RPM conditions.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] It has also been the standard material for crankcase guards on off-road motorcycles.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] Due to its high strength, low density, thermal properties, and its ability to be highly polished, 7075 is widely used in mold tool manufacturing.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] This alloy has been further refined into other 7000 series alloys for this application, namely 7050 and 7020.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] 7075 was used in the Space Shuttle SRB nozzles, and the external tank SRB beam in the Inter-tank section.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] The forward- and aft skirt as well as the Interstage of the S-II, the second stage of the Saturn V was made from 7075.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] 7075 has been sold under various trade names including Zicral/Zycral, Ergal, and Fortal Constructal.
[src:connecting-rod/7075-aluminium-alloy] Some 7000 series alloys sold under brand names for making molds include Alumec 79, Alumec 89, Contal, Certal, Alumould, and Hokotol.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Steam power has generally been superseded by the internal combustion engine or by electrical power drawn from an electrical grid.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The only steam installations that are in widespread use are the highly efficient thermal power plants used for generating electricity on a large scale.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] In contrast, the proposed steam engines may be for stationary, road, rail, or marine use.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Although most references to "Modern Steam" apply to developments since the 1970s, certain aspects of advanced steam technology can be discerned throughout the 20th century, notably automatic boiler control along with rapid startup.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] In 1922, Abner Doble developed an electro-mechanical system that reacted simultaneously to steam temperature and pressure, starting and stopping the feed pumps whilst igniting and cutting out the burner according to boiler pressure.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The contraflow monotube boiler had a working pressure of 750–1,200 psi (5.17–8.27 MPa) but contained so little water in circulation as to present no risk of explosion.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] This type of boiler was continuously developed in the US, Britain and Germany throughout the 1930s and into the 1950s for use in cars, buses, trucks, railcars, shunting locomotives (US; switchers), a speedboat and, in 1933, a converted Travel Air 2000 biplane.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] In the UK, Sentinel Waggon Works developed a vertical water-tube boiler running at 275 psi (1.90 MPa) which was used in road vehicles, shunting locomotives and railcars.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Steam could be raised much more quickly than with a conventional locomotive boiler.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Trials of the Anderson condensing system took place on Britain's Southern Railway between 1930 and 1935.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The Anderson condensing system uses a process known as mechanical vapor recompression.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] It was devised by a Glasgow marine engineer, Harry Percival Harvey Anderson.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The theory was that, by removing around 600 of the 970 British thermal units present in each pound of steam (1400 of the 2260 kilojoules in each kilogram), it would be possible to return the exhaust steam to the boiler by a pump which would consume only 1–2% of the engine's power output.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Between 1925 and 1927 Anderson, and another Glasgow engineer John McCullum (some sources give McCallum), conducted experiments on a stationary steam plant with encouraging results.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] A company, Steam Heat Conservation (SHC), was formed and a demonstration of Anderson's system was arranged at Surbiton Electricity Generating Station.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] SHC was interested in applying the system to a railway locomotive and contacted Richard Maunsell of the Southern Railway.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell requested that a controlled test be carried out at Surbiton and this was done about 1929.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell's technical assistant, Harold Holcroft, was present and a fuel saving of 29% was recorded, compared to conventional atmospheric working.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The Southern Railway converted SECR N class locomotive number A816 (later 1816 and 31816) to the Anderson system in 1930.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive underwent trials and initial results were encouraging.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The trials continued until 1934 but various problems arose, mostly with the fan for forced draught, and the project went no further.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive was converted back to standard form in 1935.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The work of French mechanical engineer André Chapelon in applying scientific analysis and a strive for thermal efficiency was an early example of advanced steam technology.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Chapelon's protégé Livio Dante Porta continued Chapelon's work.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Postwar in the late 1940s and 1950s some designers worked on modernising steam locomotives.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The Argentinian engineer Livio Dante Porta in the development of Stephensonian railway locomotives incorporating advanced steam technology was a precursor of the 'Modern Steam' movement from 1948.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Where possible, Porta much preferred to design new locomotives, but more often in practice he was forced to radically update old ones to incorporate the new technology.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] 1949 by Oliver Bulleid and the British Rail ‘Standard’ class steam locomotives of the 1950s by Robert Riddles, particularly the BR Standard Class 9F, were used to trial new steam locomotive design features, including the Franco-Crosti boiler.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] On moving to Ireland, Bulleid also designed CIÉ No.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The Sir Biscoe Tritton Lecture, given by Roger Waller, of the DLM company to the Institute of Mechanical Engineers in 2003 gives an idea of how problems in steam power are being addressed.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Waller refers mainly to some rack and pinion mountain railway locomotives that were newly built from 1992 to 1998.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] They were developed for three companies in Switzerland and Austria and continued to work on two of these lines as of 2008.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The new steam locomotives burn the same grade of light oil as their diesel counterparts, and all demonstrate the same advantages of ready availability and reduced labour cost; at the same time, they have been shown to greatly reduce air and ground pollution.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Their economic superiority has meant that they have largely replaced the diesel locomotives and railcars previously operating the line; additionally, steam locomotives are a tourist attraction.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] A parallel line of development was the return to steam power of the old Lake Geneva paddle steamer *Montreux* that had been refitted with a diesel-electric engine in the 1960s.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Economic aims similar to those achieved with the rack locomotives were pursued through automatic control of the light-oil-fired boiler and remote control of the engine from the bridge, enabling the steamship to be operated by a crew of the same size as a motor ship.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] A power unit based on advanced steam technology burning fossil fuel will inevitably emit carbon dioxide, a long-lasting greenhouse gas.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] However, significant reductions of other pollutants such as CO and NOx are achievable by steam compared to other combustion technologies, since it does not involve explosive combustion, thus removing the need for add-ons (such as filters) or special preparation of fuel.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] If renewable fuel such as wood or other biofuel is used then the system could be carbon neutral.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The use of biofuel remains controversial; however, liquid biofuels are easier to manufacture for steam plant than for diesels as they do not demand the stringent fuel standards required to protect diesel injectors.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] In principle, combustion and power delivery of steam plant can be considered separate stages.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] High overall thermal efficiency may be difficult to achieve, largely due to the extra stage of generating a working fluid between combustion and power delivery attributable mainly to leakages and heat losses.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The separation of the processes allows specific problems to be addressed at each stage without revising the whole system every time.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] For instance, the boiler or steam generator can be adapted to use any heat source, whether obtained from solid, liquid or gaseous fuel, and can use waste heat.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Whatever the choice, it will have no direct effect on the design of the engine unit, as that only ever has to deal with steam.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] This project mainly includes combined electrical generation and heating systems for private homes and small villages burning wood or bamboo chips.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] This is intended to replace 2-stroke donkey engines and small diesel power plants.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Drastic reduction in noise level is one immediate benefit of a steam-powered small plant.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Ted Pritchard, of Melbourne, Australia, was intensively developing this type of unit from 2002 until his death in 2007.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The company Pritchard Power (now Uniflow Power) stated in 2010 that they continue to develop the stationary S5000, and that a prototype had been built and was being tested, and designs were being refined for market ready products.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Until 2006 a German company called *Enginion* was actively developing a *Steamcell*, a micro CHP unit about the size of a PC tower for domestic use.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] It seems that by 2008 it had merged with Berlin company AMOVIS.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Since 2012, a French company, EXOES, is selling to industrial firms a Rankine Cycle, patented, engine, which is designed to work with many fuels such as concentrated solar power, biomass, or fossil.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The system, called "SHAPE" for Sustainable Heat And Power Engine, converts the heat into electricity.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The SHAPE engine is suitable for embedded, and stationary, applications.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] A SHAPE engine has been integrated into a biomass boiler, and into a Concentrated solar power system.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The company is planning to work with automobile manufactures, long-haul truck manufactures, and railway corporations.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] A similar unit is marketed by Powertherm, a subsidiary of Spilling (see below).
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] A company in India manufactures steam-powered generators in a range of sizes from 4 hp to 50 hp.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] They also offer a number of different mills that can be powered by their engines.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] In matter of technology, notice that the Quasiturbine is a uniflow rotary steam engine where steam intakes in hot areas, while exhausting in cold areas.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The Spilling company produces a variety of small fixed stationary plant adapted to biomass combustion or power derived from waste heat or pressure recovery.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The Finnish company Steammotor Finland has developed a small rotary steam engine that runs with 800 kW steam generator.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The engines are planned to produce electricity in wood chip fired power plants.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] According to the company, the steam engine named *Quadrum* generates 27% efficiency and runs with 180 °C steam at 8 bar pressure, while a corresponding steam turbine produces just 15% efficiency, requires steam temperature of 240 °C and pressure of 40 bar.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The high efficiency comes from a patented crank mechanism, that gives a smooth, pulseless torque.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] The company believes that by further developing the construction there is potential to reach as high efficiency as 30–35%.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] During the first 1970s oil crisis, a number of investigations into steam technology were initiated by large automobile corporations although as the crisis died down, impetus was soon lost.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Australian engineer Ted Pritchard's main field of research from the late 1950s until the 1970s was the building of several efficient steam power units working on the uniflow system adapted to a small truck and two cars.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] One of the cars was achieving the lowest emissions figures of that time.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] All these engines made heavy use of flameless ceramic heat cells both for the steam generator and at strategic boost points where steam was injected into the cylinder(s).
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] A design mounted on power bogies with compact water-tube boiler similar to Sentinel designs of the 1930s.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Example: Sentinel-Cammell locomotive (right).
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Both 52 8055 and the proposed 5AT are of conventional layout, with the cab at the back, while the ACE 3000 had the cab located at the front.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Other approaches are possible, especially with liquid fuel firing.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] This is a well-tried design with the potential for a large power output and would provide the driver good visibility.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Another well-tried design with large power potential.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] A future design could include shorter water tanks, and a cab at each end, to give the driver a good view in either direction.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] Another proposal for advanced steam technology is to revive the fireless locomotive, which runs on stored steam independently pre-generated.
[src:connecting-rod/advanced-steam-technology] An example is the Solar Steam Train project in Sacramento, California.
[src:connecting-rod/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:connecting-rod/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:connecting-rod/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:connecting-rod/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:connecting-rod/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:connecting-rod/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:connecting-rod/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:connecting-rod/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:connecting-rod/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:connecting-rod/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:connecting-rod/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:connecting-rod/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:connecting-rod/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:connecting-rod/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:connecting-rod/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:connecting-rod/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:connecting-rod/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:connecting-rod/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:connecting-rod/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] A **connecting rod**, also called a '**con rod'**, is the part of a piston engine which connects the piston to the crankshaft.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] Together with the crank, the connecting rod converts the reciprocating motion of the piston into the rotation of the crankshaft.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] The connecting rod is required to transmit the compressive and tensile forces from the piston.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] In its most common form, in an internal combustion engine, it allows pivoting on the piston end and rotation on the shaft end.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] The predecessor to the connecting rod is a mechanic linkage used by water mills to convert rotating motion of the water wheel into reciprocating motion.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] The most common usage of connecting rods is in internal combustion engines or on steam engines.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] A connecting rod crank has been found in the Celtic Oppida at Paule in Brittany, dated to 69 BC.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] The predecessor to the connecting length is the mechanical linkage used by Roman-era watermills.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] An early example of this linkage has been found at the late 3rd century Hierapolis sawmill in Roman Asia (modern Turkey) and the 6th century saw mills at Ephesus in Asia Minor (modern Turkey) and at Gerasa in Roman Syria.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] The crank and connecting rod mechanism of these machines converted the rotary motion of the waterwheel into the linear movement of the saw blades.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] There is also documentation of cranks with connecting rods in the sketch books of Taccola from Renaissance Italy and 15th century painter Pisanello.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] The 1712 Newcomen atmospheric engine (the first steam engine) used chain drive instead of a connecting rod, since the piston only produced force in one direction.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] However, most steam engines after this are double-acting, therefore the force is produced in both directions, leading to the use of a connecting rod.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] The typical arrangement uses a large sliding bearing block called a crosshead with the hinge between the piston and connecting rod placed outside the cylinder, requiring a seal around the piston rod.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] In a steam locomotive, the cranks are usually mounted directly on the driving wheels.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] The connecting rod is used between the crank pin on the wheel and the crosshead (where it connects to the piston rod).
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] On smaller steam locomotives, the connecting rods are usually of rectangular cross-section; however, marine-type rods of circular cross-section have occasionally been used.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] On paddle steamers, the connecting rods are called 'pitmans' (not to be mistaken for pitman arms).
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] A connecting rod for an internal combustion engine consists of the 'big end', 'rod' and 'small end'.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] The small end attaches to the gudgeon pin (also called 'piston pin' or 'wrist pin' in the U.S.), which allows for rotation between the connecting rod and the piston.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] Typically, the big end connects to the crankpin using a plain bearing to reduce friction; however, some smaller engines may instead use a rolling-element bearing, in order to avoid the need for a pumped lubrication system.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] Connecting rods with rolling element bearings are typically a one-piece design where the crankshaft must be pressed together through them, rather than a two-piece design that can be bolted around the journal of a one-piece crankshaft.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] Typically there is a pinhole bored through the bearing on the big end of the connecting rod so that lubricating oil squirts out onto the thrust side of the cylinder wall to lubricate the travel of the pistons and piston rings.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] A connecting rod can rotate at both ends, so that the angle between the connecting rod and the piston can change as the rod moves up and down and rotates around the crankshaft.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] The materials used for connecting rods widely vary, including carbon steel, iron base sintered metal, micro-alloyed steel, spheroidized graphite cast iron.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] In mass-produced automotive engines, the connecting rods are most usually made of steel.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] In high performance applications, "billet" connecting rods can be used, which are machined out of a solid billet of metal, rather than being cast or forged.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] Other materials include T6-2024 aluminium alloy or T651-7075 aluminium alloy, which are used for lightness and the ability to absorb high impact at the expense of durability.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] Titanium is a more expensive option which reduces the weight.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] Cast iron can be used for cheaper, lower performance applications such as motor scooters.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] During each rotation of the crankshaft, a connecting rod is often subject to large and repetitive forces: shear forces due to the angle between the piston and the crankpin, compression forces as the piston moves downwards, and tensile forces as the piston moves upwards.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] These forces are proportional to the engine speed (RPM) squared.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] Failure of a connecting rod, often called "throwing a rod", often forces the broken rod through the side of the crankcase and thereby renders the engine irreparable.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] Common causes of connecting rod failure are tensile failure from high engine speeds, the impact force when the piston hits a valve (due to a valvetrain problem), rod bearing failure (usually due to a lubrication problem), or incorrect installation of the connecting rod.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] The sideways force exerted on the piston through the connecting rod by the crankshaft can cause the cylinders to wear into an oval shape.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] This significantly reduces engine performance, since the circular piston rings are unable to properly seal against the oval-shaped cylinder walls.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] The amount of sideways force is proportional to the angle of the connecting rod, therefore longer connecting rods will reduce the amount of sideways force and engine wear.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] However, the maximum length of a connecting rod is constrained by the engine block size; the stroke length plus the connecting rod length must not result in the piston travelling past the top of the engine block.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] Radial engines typically use master-and-slave connecting rods, whereby one piston (the uppermost piston in the animation), has a master rod with a direct attachment to the crankshaft.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] The remaining pistons pin their connecting rods' attachments to rings around the edge of the master rod.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] Multi-bank engines with many cylinders, such as V12 engines, have little space available for many connecting rod journals on a limited length of crankshaft.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] Another solution is to use master-and-slave connecting rods, where the master rod also includes one or more ring pins which are connected to the big ends of slave rods on other cylinders.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] A drawback of master–slave rods is that the stroke lengths of all slave pistons not located 180° from the master piston will always be slightly longer than that of the master piston, which increases vibration in V engines.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] One of the most complicated examples of master-and-slave connecting rods is the 24-cylinder Junkers Jumo 222 experimental airplane engine developed for World War II.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] This engine consisted of six banks of cylinders, each with four cylinders per bank.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] Each "layer" of six cylinders used one master connecting rod, with the other five cylinders using slave rods.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] Approximately 300 test engines were built, but the engine did not reach production.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] Fork-and-blade rods, also known as "split big-end rods", have been used on V-twin motorcycle engines and V12 aircraft engines.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] For each pair of cylinders, a "fork" rod is split in two at the big end and the "blade" rod from the opposing cylinder is thinned to fit into this gap in the fork.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] This arrangement removes the rocking couple that is caused when cylinder pairs are offset along the crankshaft.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] A common arrangement for the big-end bearing is for the fork rod to have a single wide bearing sleeve that spans the whole width of the rod, including the central gap.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] The blade rod then runs, not directly on the crankpin, but on the outside of this sleeve.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] This causes the two rods to oscillate back and forth (instead of rotating relative to each other), which reduces the forces on the bearing and the surface speed.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] However, the bearing movement also becomes reciprocating rather than continuously rotating, which is a more difficult problem for lubrication.
[src:connecting-rod/connecting-rod] Notable engines to use fork-and-blade rods include the Rolls-Royce Merlin V12 aircraft engine, EMD two-stroke Diesel engines, and various Harley Davidson V-twin motorcycle engines.
